			<header class="header">
				<h1>Map Sensor Editor</h1>

				<style>
				.marge {
					margin-left: 5em;
				}
				</style>
				
				<button id="help" class="btn btn-6 btn-6i littleButton help" style="font-size:20px; padding:6px 20px; margin:10px 0px; ">Help</button>
				<center><div id="helpDetail" style="width:900px;display:none;padding:20px 50px; border-radius:  40px;box-shadow: -1px 2px 5px 1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.7),
            -1px 2px 20px rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.6) inset;  ">
				<h2>I. Connecting to the server</h2>	
				<p align="left" class="marge">Start by connecting to the server with the connection button located on the panel on your left
				</p>
				
				<h2>II. Load a new map</h2>
				<p align="left" class="marge">To create a new map load an image using the button
				Load image by entering the path of the associated image (jpeg, jpeg2000, jpg, png ...)
				</p>
				
				<h2>III. Add sensors on your map</h2>
				<p align="left" class="marge">After logging in to the server and the sensors connected to it you can see in the section "Add Sensor" all the sensors connected to the server in the drop-down list "Sensor Selected". You can hang one of these sensors on your map by selecting two points that will define the coordinates of your sensor on your map. To do this, place the cursor of your mouse on the loaded card then press the key ENTER of your keyboard. Then you can add the sensor using the button "Add" in the same section or cancel Selected contact with the "Cancel" button.
				</p>
				
				<h2>IV. Add Area on your map</h2>
				<p align="left" class="marge">
				You can add areas on your map that will later allow you to display the number of people present on it in real time. This automatic management is done by associating a sensor assembly on a area (a sensor separates 2 neighboring areas). When a sensor activates an algorithm will alter) the number of persons present in the zones separated by this sensor. To add an area first enter a name in the "Name" field in the "Add area" section. You can also set the number of people in the "Number of people" field to the radius of the disc that will be displayed on the map via the "Ray" field. Once these parameters are set to your convenience place your cursor at the desired coordinates on the cards and press the CTRL key on your keyboard.
				</p>
				
				<h2>V. Create link between Areas and Sensors</h2>
				<p align="left" class="marge">Once your sensors and zones have been added to the maps, you only have to connect the sensors with the neighboring zones. To do this, go to the "Create link" section on the right panel and select the two adjacent zones "Area_A" and "Area_B" as well as the separator sensor in the "IdSensor" drop-down list. You will notice that the sensors in the "IdSensor" drop-down list are the ones that have been added to your map.				
				</p>
				
